05568nam a22008295i 9781400845170DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2012    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008451707 a10.1515/97814008451702doi  a(DE-B1597)453846  a(OCoLC)979742310  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aQ124.97b.B43 2017 7aHIS0370102bisacsh04a508.5809022231 aBeckwith, Christopher I., eauthor.10aWarriors of the Cloisters :bThe Central Asian Origins of Science in the Medieval World /cChristopher I. Beckwith.  aCourse Book 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2012] 4c©2013  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations and Transcription of Foreign Languages -- tChapter One. Introduction -- tChapter Two. The Recursive Argument Method of Medieval Science -- tChapter Three. From College and Universitas to University -- tChapter Four. Buddhist Central Asian Invention of the Method -- tChapter Five. Islamization in Classical Arabic Central Asia -- tChapter Six. Transmission to Medieval Western Europe -- tChapter Seven. India, Tibet, China, Byzantium, and Other Control Cases -- tChapter Eight. Conclusion -- tAppendix A: On the Latin Translations of Avicenna's Works -- tAppendix B: On Peter of Poitiers -- tAppendix C: The Charter of the Collège des Dix-huit -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWarriors of the Cloisters tells how key cultural innovations from Central Asia revolutionized medieval Europe and gave rise to the culture of science in the West. Medieval scholars rarely performed scientific experiments, but instead contested issues in natural science, philosophy, and theology using the recursive argument method. This highly distinctive and unusual method of disputation was a core feature of medieval science, the predecessor of modern science. We know that the foundations of science were imported to Western Europe from the Islamic world, but until now the origins of such key elements of Islamic culture have been a mystery. In this provocative book, Christopher I. Beckwith traces how the recursive argument method was first developed by Buddhist scholars and was spread by them throughout ancient Central Asia. He shows how the method was adopted by Islamic Central Asian natural philosophers--most importantly by Avicenna, one of the most brilliant of all medieval thinkers--and transmitted to the West when Avicenna's works were translated into Latin in Spain in the twelfth century by the Jewish philosopher Ibn Da'ud and others. During the same period the institution of the college was also borrowed from the Islamic world. The college was where most of the disputations were held, and became the most important component of medieval Europe's newly formed universities. As Beckwith demonstrates, the Islamic college also originated in Buddhist Central Asia. Using in-depth analysis of ancient Buddhist, Classical Arabic, and Medieval Latin writings, Warriors of the Cloisters transforms our understanding of the origins of medieval scientific culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aAcademic disputations. 0aSciencezAsia, CentralxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aScience, Medieval. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066258008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014z97831